Observation Details: Continuing. Seen in the channel on the right side of the trail, specifically, to the east of the east pond, about 3/4 of the way from the trailhead to the north bend of the pond. We saw the bird near a large flock of Mallards, but we were able to identify the Brant by the black head, slightly larger size than Mallard, brown body, and larger white rump. We observed the bird swimming back and forth with the Mallards in the channel for about 10 minutes before deciding to move on.
Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Location: Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Observation Details: Seen by Aaron Sun, João Menezes, and Jesse Harrison at 11:15am standing at (42.31443, -72.60670) while looking out towards the field on the east. Initially seen and quickly identified as Plovers. Identified more precisely to be American Golden Plover by Jesse Harrison. They were standing by the edge of a puddle and walking within the dirt field. The birds were medium-sized, tall and slender shorebirds with a slender bill when compared to Black-bellied Plovers. Color was difficult to assess due to distance, but generally perceived to be mainly gray. Also, long primaries separate from tail. Photos attached. Seen walking around for about 15 minutes. We found the birds blended in very well with the dirt and potato field, as they were very difficult to spot.

Location: Sonny Bono Salton Sea NWR--Vendel Rd.
Observation Details: Woohoo! After scanning the second pond south of the Unit 1 parking for about 10 minutes, we spotted a Stilt Sandpiper in the northeast corner, at about (33.0799871, -115.7104158). It gave us excellent prolonged looks as it foraged, mixing more with the dowitchers and ibises than with the peeps. Much larger than Western Sandpipers; slightly taller than dowitchers, but slimmer and smaller overall. Bill long and ever so slightly decurved, but shorter than dowitcher bills. Long, yellow legs. Overall, very gray with no brownish tones. Whenever the Stilt Sandpiper bent over to forage, we noted the primaries and tertials were very ruffled, giving it an almost hedgehog-like appearance, making it easy to pick out from among the dowitchers. Photos to be uploaded.

Observation Details: Continuing among Western Sandpipers in the southwest corner of Pond 23. First seen around 9:30 am, on the far, low patch of mud at (32.5919947, -117.1140087). Then, it flew to “stint island”, where it first foraged on the low side of the island at (32.5913097, -117.1132889), and then continued foraging behind the mounds on the right side of the island, out of sight from the viewing platform. The stint stood out readily from the Western Sandpipers next to it. The key field marks we all noted, relative to WESA: a scalier, browner back, a much shorter, slightly decurved bill, and smaller size overall. The legs were black, seen in good lighting from multiple angles. In the scope and binoculars, we could not clearly discern the distinctive facial pattern with the split supercilium, which troubled us, until we took photos that clearly showed the same facial pattern as the Little Stint. Photos to be uploaded soon.

Observation Details: EDIT: We now think this is a juvenile Western Sandpiper.    Saw an interesting peep on the mudflats as we were about to leave that we now believe is a juvenile Semipalmated - see attached photos. The legs are black, ruling out Least. The bill is quite short, with no pronounced droop at the tip like on a Western. The scapulars have some orange coloration, but it looks to be within the range of the brightest Semipalmated. Overall, the tones on the head, neck, and back are buffy - warmer than the whites, reds, and grays typical of Western. The back feathers are edged in white, making the bird a juvenile. This is our ID assessment, but any feedback is welcome.

Observation Details: Interesting individual noticed several days later in photos taken by Aaron of the entire flock. The bird in question is in the center of the images, with an apparently extremely short bill that looks to be outside of the range of variation for WESA. We asked Steve Rottenborn for help on the ID, and he thought the breast, head, and upperpart patterning looked better for SESA rather than WESA. The photos show less rufous and dark coloration on this bird's scapulars than those of the adjacent WESA. This bird also looks slightly smaller than nearby WESA. However, we never observed this bird in the field, and bill shape and length can be difficult to judge from photos (especially of this quality) so we would prefer to leave it as a slash to be safe, even though in all likelihood this is a SESA.

Best shorebirding we’ve seen here so far this year - great numbers of WESA and phalaropes. But there was something missing… With Laura Forrest for most of the time, so putting 3 observers. Interestingly, when we came back here around 11:30 am after checking New Chicago Marsh, the vast majority of WESA were gone from the pond. Around 12:30 pm, there were more, but still much fewer than in the early morning.

I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Observation Details: Amazing numbers of Thayer’s Iceland Gulls in the gull flock on the dry mud of A13. This number is an estimate of the gulls we are sure were Thayer’s: petite-billed, dark-irised, with smudgy streaks on the head, and size intermediate between California and Herring. There were many other birds that could have been Thayer’s, which exhibited some, but not all, of the above characteristics (these are under Larus sp.). We both agreed that early in the afternoon, the dominant species in the flock was Thayer’s, not Herring. Later in the afternoon, as gulls flew in to join the flock, Herring became more prevalent, but there was still a staggering number of Thayer’s. The total number of gulls in the flock by the end of the day was probably upwards of 2000, so 300 Thayer’s is likely an undercount.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Observation Details: Flying over the parking lot to the ocean.

Location: Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)
Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Location: Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Location: Vina Vieja, Gwinn and Sunnyslope Parks
Observation Details: Flew into a tree in the northwest corner of Vina Vieja Park, sat there for a minute, and then dipped back into the vegetation along Eaton Wash, where we couldn’t refind it, despite much effort. Our impression was of a rather small empid, with bright yellow belly contrasting with gray breast, eyering shape unlike that of Pac-slope, and rather short bill. The bill looked too short for Gray, and the tail was not being wagged downwards. We did not get a good read on the primary projection or tail length in the field. Tristan got one photo, but it is unfortunately too blurry to interpret the primary projection or tail length, and the bird’s head is turned away, with the bill not visible. We feel it is safest to leave this bird as Hammond’s/Dusky Flycatcher, but reviewer feedback on the photo is welcome.

Location: Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)
Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Location: Joseph D. Grant CP--ranch house area
Observation Details: We were feeling hopeless and empty as we walked back from the ranchhouse, unable to see our goal. As we walked back to the trail, we decided to pass by the benches where we saw another birder standing and taking photos. "There it is!" I said to my companion, Tristan. Above the benches, perched in a branch was the bright-red Vermillion Flycatcher. We observed it's red body, black back and black eyestripe in glorious detail as it flew towards the south. We chased it briefly and took photos before departing, for a total observation time of approximately 5 minutes.

Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Observing the giant gull flock on the mud of A13. Many gulls were streaming in from the south, and some streaming out towards the more distant salt ponds for the duration of the observation, so the total number of gulls increased from around 1500 to likely over 2000. Interestingly, there were no gulls on the A12 islands when we passed by them on our way back to Alviso Marina.

Mudflats along the creek bank and a patch far out along the creek in SM were already uncovered when we arrived, at 3.5 hrs after high tide, height around 5 ft. Probably ideal to arrive around height 6 ft, right before tide begins to expose mudflats.

Location: Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Location: Sunnyvale WPCP (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Location: Sonny Bono Salton Sea NWR--Vendel Rd.
Observation Details: Rattle call heard from the field on the east side of Vendel Rd, just south of the Unit 1 parking, as soon as we parked around 3:50 pm, but not heard again. Clearly coming from a bird moving in flight, at least several hundred feet out into the field, but the bird itself was never seen. We heard maybe 4 or 5 phrases before the bird went silent (presumably landed). The calls sounded drier than the Lapland Longspur recordings in the Merlin app, but perhaps still ok for that species. We didn’t hear any “tew” calls interspersed between the rattle calls. Wished we could have looked for the longspur, but we decided to look for Stilt Sandpiper in the ponds to the west of the road instead, and it paid off!

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

Location: Ed Levin County Park (please use a more specific hotspot where possible)

Checklist Comments: I had decided to take a break this afternoon per the suggestion of my friend, Tristan. We headed out towards the Sunnyvale WPCP in order to look for Brant. About a week ago, we had come here in the evening to look for Brant but to no avail. Sadly, we saw that people had seen Brant in the spot we looked just the day before and the day after. Then, Tristan went again and looped around three times without seeing it. Despite our previous failures, this time we were determined to find the goose. We parked on the street outside the pollution plant because Tristan had seen the plant parking lot was closed on Monday. We got our bikes from outside of the trunk and then rode together to the east pond. Along the way, Tristan was trying out his new camera and photographing Common Gallinules and Ruddy Duck. We continued biking before we were confronted by a wall of Mallard, Dowitchers, and Pelicans. We slowly progressed through, when suddenly I saw a goose with a black head and neck in the channel to the right of the trail. Without thinking, I exclaimed "Isn't that it? Isn't that Brant?" Tristan and I were elated to see that it was indeed Brant, swimming near the huge flock of Mallards we had seen earlier. We watched it swim back and forth in the channel among the Mallards. Tristan commented that it looked very similar to the Mallards, but I thought the white rump and black head made it stand out, although the size was only slightly bigger. We watched it for around 10 minutes before heading back home. We were very pleased with the outing: I had gotten my 300th species (Brant) and Tristan got his 150th and 151st (Long-billed Dowitcher and Brant). However we decided to just say Brant was 150th and Dowitcher was 151st.

We were looking at a Western Bluebird perched on the lightpost when we heard a clear, loud and sharp call coming from the tree beside us. We saw the Painted Redstart hopping between branches in the tree. In flight, the bird appeared mostly black with red flashes. Once it landed, we clearly saw the large white wingbars, black body, and red belly. The bird remained moving around in the tree for about a minute or two before we lost it. We continued searching but weren't able to refind it. Photos attached.
